649
01:00:05,622 --> 01:00:07,040
Fred Hamill, Pathfinders 101st.

650
01:00:07,123 --> 01:00:09,042
John Miller, 2nd Rangers.

651
01:00:09,125 --> 01:00:11,169
Thank you.

652
01:00:11,252 --> 01:00:13,505
We're looking for Private James Ryan.

653
01:00:13,588 --> 01:00:17,383
He's part of your outfit. Any chance you policed him up?

654
01:00:17,467 --> 01:00:20,678
- How was the road in? - Scenic.

655
01:00:20,762 --> 01:00:22,764
We lost most of our ammo.

656
01:00:22,847 --> 01:00:25,016
And one of our men.

657
01:00:25,099 --> 01:00:28,436
Lieutenant, redeploy that bazooka to the right side.

658
01:00:28,520 --> 01:00:29,646
Yes, sir!

659
01:00:29,729 --> 01:00:31,648
And get Ryan up here.

660
01:00:33,149 --> 01:00:34,609
Ryan!

661
01:00:34,692 --> 01:00:37,028
Ryan, front and centre!

662
01:00:37,111 --> 01:00:38,780
Ryan!

663
01:00:42,158 --> 01:00:43,618
Here comes our boy.

664
01:00:50,959 --> 01:00:53,086
Told you he was an asshole.

665
01:00:55,421 --> 01:00:57,048
Sir, Private Ryan reporting.

666
01:00:57,131 --> 01:00:58,633
At ease.

667
01:00:58,716 --> 01:01:02,220
Captain Miller, 2nd Rangers. He wants a word with you.

668
01:01:03,930 --> 01:01:06,057
This way.

669
01:01:06,140 --> 01:01:07,642
All right.

670
01:01:07,725 --> 01:01:09,102
Take a knee.

671
01:01:18,194 --> 01:01:20,864
Private, l have some bad news.

672
01:01:29,247 --> 01:01:33,376
Well, there isn't any easy way to say this, so, uh...

673
01:01:35,211 --> 01:01:39,048
so l'll just say it - your brothers are dead.

674
01:01:39,132 --> 01:01:44,888
We have, uh, orders to come get you...

675
01:01:44,971 --> 01:01:46,472
'cause you're going home.

676
01:02:00,904 --> 01:02:03,406
Oh, my God. My brothers are dead.

677
01:02:09,370 --> 01:02:13,500
l was gonna take 'em fishing when we got home.

678
01:02:28,723 --> 01:02:30,225
l'm so sorry, James.

679
01:02:30,308 --> 01:02:32,769
l can't tell you how much.

680
01:02:32,852 --> 01:02:35,647
How...how did they die?

681
01:02:35,730 --> 01:02:38,608
They were killed in action.

682
01:02:38,691 --> 01:02:42,820
No, that can't be. They're both...

683
01:02:42,904 --> 01:02:45,031
That...that can't be.

684
01:02:45,114 --> 01:02:49,077
My brothers are still in grammar school.

685
01:02:50,703 --> 01:02:52,747
You're James Ryan?

686
01:02:52,831 --> 01:02:54,499
Yeah.

687
01:02:54,582 --> 01:02:57,794
James Francis Ryan from lowa?

688
01:02:57,877 --> 01:03:00,672
James Frederick Ryan, Minnesota.

689
01:03:06,344 --> 01:03:09,722
Well, does that...does that mean my brothers are OK?

690
01:03:09,806 --> 01:03:11,641
Yeah, l'm sure they're fine.

691
01:03:11,724 --> 01:03:13,685
Are you sure they're OK, though?

692
01:03:13,768 --> 01:03:16,729
We're looking for a different Private Ryan.

693
01:03:16,813 --> 01:03:18,606
How do you know?

694
01:03:18,690 --> 01:03:20,859
How do you know the foul-up

695
01:03:20,942 --> 01:03:23,486
isn't that his brothers are OK and that...

696
01:03:23,570 --> 01:03:25,780
Lieutenant, l'm sorry for the trouble.

697
01:03:25,864 --> 01:03:30,702
l just wrote them a letter... l got to get home.

698
01:03:30,785 --> 01:03:34,455
l got to get home right now.

699
01:03:34,539 --> 01:03:36,166
Shh, take it easy.

700
01:03:36,249 --> 01:03:38,585
- Where's our Ryan? - l don't know.

701
01:03:38,668 --> 01:03:40,336
You in touch with your CO?

702
01:03:40,420 --> 01:03:43,131
- That figures. - What unit's he in?

703
01:03:43,214 --> 01:03:44,716
Baker Company, 506.

704
01:03:44,799 --> 01:03:48,011
- The guy with the broken foot? - Charlie, l think.

705
01:03:48,094 --> 01:03:49,304
You think? Yeah.

706
01:03:49,387 --> 01:03:52,140
Ryan? Don't know... Man!

707
01:03:52,223 --> 01:03:54,392
Where was your drop zone?

708
01:03:54,475 --> 01:03:55,852
Just inside of Vierville.

709
01:03:55,935 --> 01:03:58,855
Vierville? How did you end up here?

710
01:03:58,938 --> 01:04:00,064
You got me, sir.

711
01:04:00,148 --> 01:04:02,025
C-47 took heavy fire.

712
01:04:02,108 --> 01:04:05,111
Pilot tried to get out, turning every which way.

713
01:04:05,195 --> 01:04:09,199
Took more fire in the drop. Got messy. l ended up here.

714
01:04:09,282 --> 01:04:12,660
l haven't seen a single guy from my stick, sir.

715
01:04:12,744 --> 01:04:16,331
Anybody there have a big mouth, say where the drop was?

716
01:04:16,414 --> 01:04:20,001
No, sir, but they had the same rally point as us.

717
01:04:20,084 --> 01:04:21,961
Show me.

718
01:04:22,045 --> 01:04:23,588
My men are beat.

719
01:04:23,671 --> 01:04:27,717
We'll hold up for three hours then pull out after dark.

720
01:04:27,800 --> 01:04:31,721
Got anything left in this town like a three-star hotel?

721
01:04:31,804 --> 01:04:34,641
Something with clean sheets and room service?

722
01:04:34,724 --> 01:04:36,643
How about a nice comfy church?

723
01:04:36,726 --> 01:04:39,062
- We'll take that. - Any news?

724
01:04:39,145 --> 01:04:40,647
How's it all falling together?

725
01:04:40,730 --> 01:04:42,607
Well, we got the beachhead secure.

726
01:04:42,690 --> 01:04:45,443
Problem is Monty's taking his time moving on Caen.

727
01:04:45,527 --> 01:04:48,071
We can't pull out till he's ready, so...

728
01:04:48,154 --> 01:04:49,155
That guy's overrated.

729
01:04:49,239 --> 01:04:50,532
No argument here.

730
01:04:50,615 --> 01:04:53,368
You got to take Caen so you can take Saint-Lo.

731
01:04:53,451 --> 01:04:55,453
Take Saint-Lo to take Valognes.

732
01:04:55,537 --> 01:04:57,080
Valognes, you got Cherbourg.

733
01:04:57,163 --> 01:04:58,623
And Cherbourg, you got Paris.

734
01:04:58,706 --> 01:05:01,042
Paris, you get Berlin.

735
01:05:01,125 --> 01:05:03,127
Then that big boat home.

736
01:05:05,255 --> 01:05:08,216
We sure could use you around here,

737
01:05:08,299 --> 01:05:10,093
but l understand what you're doing.

738
01:05:10,176 --> 01:05:11,344
You do?

739
01:05:11,427 --> 01:05:14,681
Yeah. l got a couple of brothers myself.

740
01:05:14,764 --> 01:05:17,100
- Oh. - Good luck.

741
01:05:17,183 --> 01:05:18,309
Thank you.

742
01:05:18,393 --> 01:05:20,061
No, l mean it.

743
01:05:20,144 --> 01:05:22,689
Find him. Get him home.

744
01:05:30,864 --> 01:05:33,158
What's with your hand?

745
01:05:33,241 --> 01:05:35,535
l don't know.

746
01:05:37,162 --> 01:05:40,957
lt started when they brought us down for embarkation.

747
01:05:41,040 --> 01:05:42,500
lt comes and goes.

748
01:05:42,584 --> 01:05:45,795
You may have to get yourself a new job.

749
01:05:45,879 --> 01:05:49,090
This one doesn't seem to agree with you any more.

750
01:05:54,304 --> 01:05:55,471
What?

751
01:05:59,309 --> 01:06:01,519
- What? - Nothing.

752
01:06:01,603 --> 01:06:04,522
What was the name of that kid at Anzio?

753
01:06:04,606 --> 01:06:07,609
He was always walking around on his hands,

754
01:06:07,692 --> 01:06:11,613
and singing that song about the man on the flying trapeze?

755
01:06:20,079 --> 01:06:21,456
Yeah, Vecchio.

756
01:06:21,539 --> 01:06:23,917
He was a goofy kid.

757
01:06:24,000 --> 01:06:28,213
Remember he used to pee a ''V'' on everybody's jacket,

758
01:06:28,296 --> 01:06:30,381
for Vecchio.

759
01:06:30,465 --> 01:06:31,758
For victory.

760
01:06:31,841 --> 01:06:33,176
Vecchio.

761
01:06:36,012 --> 01:06:37,388
He was so short.

762
01:06:37,472 --> 01:06:41,351
- Wasn't he a midget? - How did he become a Ranger?

763
01:06:43,978 --> 01:06:46,231
Got shot in the foot once.

764
01:06:46,314 --> 01:06:48,733
He could walk faster on his hands.

765
01:06:50,735 --> 01:06:53,363
He could run faster on his hands than...

766
01:07:09,128 --> 01:07:15,677
You see, when...you end up killing one of your men,

767
01:07:15,760 --> 01:07:18,847
you tell yourself it happened

768
01:07:18,930 --> 01:07:26,062
so you could save the lives of two or three or 10 others.

769
01:07:26,145 --> 01:07:28,106
Maybe a hundred others.

770
01:07:31,276 --> 01:07:35,363
Do you know how many men l've lost under my command?

771
01:07:35,446 --> 01:07:38,741
- How many? - 94.

772
01:07:38,825 --> 01:07:42,495
But that means l've saved the lives

773
01:07:42,579 --> 01:07:44,831
of 10 times that many, doesn't it?

774
01:07:44,914 --> 01:07:47,917
Maybe even 20, right?

775
01:07:48,001 --> 01:07:49,377
20 times as many?

776
01:07:55,133 --> 01:07:57,385
And that's how simple it is.

777
01:07:58,428 --> 01:08:00,638
That's how you...

778
01:08:00,722 --> 01:08:03,892
That's how you rationalise making the choice

779
01:08:03,975 --> 01:08:07,145
between the mission and the men.

780
01:08:07,228 --> 01:08:10,190
Except this time, this mission is a man.

781
01:08:13,610 --> 01:08:16,070
This Ryan better be worth it.

782
01:08:19,115 --> 01:08:22,035
He'd better go home and cure some disease

783
01:08:22,118 --> 01:08:26,039
or invent a longer-lasting light bulb or something.

784
01:08:26,122 --> 01:08:31,002
l wouldn't trade 10 Ryans for one Vecchio or one Caparzo.

785
01:08:31,085 --> 01:08:32,921
Amen.

786
01:08:34,047 --> 01:08:37,175
Look. There it goes again.

787
01:08:37,258 --> 01:08:38,593
Sir...

788
01:08:38,676 --> 01:08:41,596
are you all right?

789
01:08:46,100 --> 01:08:49,020
Look, we're gonna move out in two hours.

790
01:08:49,103 --> 01:08:50,897
Why don't you get some sleep?

791
01:08:50,980 --> 01:08:53,691
l don't know how he does it.

792
01:08:53,775 --> 01:08:55,068
What's that?

793
01:08:55,151 --> 01:08:57,779
Falls asleep like that. Look at him.

794
01:08:57,862 --> 01:09:00,698
He's lights-out the minute his head's down.

795
01:09:00,782 --> 01:09:02,116
Clear conscience.

796
01:09:02,200 --> 01:09:06,830
What's that saying? ''lf God's on our side, who's on theirs?''

797
01:09:06,913 --> 01:09:10,166
''lf God be for us, who could be against us?''

798
01:09:10,250 --> 01:09:11,668
Yeah, what did l say?

799
01:09:11,751 --> 01:09:13,169
Well, actually,

800
01:09:13,253 --> 01:09:16,631
the trick to falling asleep is trying to stay awake.

801
01:09:16,714 --> 01:09:18,591
How is that, Wade?

802
01:09:18,675 --> 01:09:23,346
My mother was an intern, she worked late nights,

803
01:09:23,429 --> 01:09:25,306
slept through the day,

804
01:09:25,390 --> 01:09:29,602
so the only time we got to talk was when she'd get home.

805
01:09:29,686 --> 01:09:34,274
So l used to lie in my bed and try to stay awake,

806
01:09:34,357 --> 01:09:37,777
but it never worked 'cause the harder l tried,

807
01:09:37,861 --> 01:09:39,904
the faster l'd fall asleep.

808
01:09:40,613 --> 01:09:43,158
That wouldn't have mattered in my house.

809
01:09:43,241 --> 01:09:46,578
My ma would've shook me awake, chatted till dawn.

810
01:09:46,661 --> 01:09:49,664
That woman was never too tired to talk.

811
01:09:49,747 --> 01:09:53,209
Probably the only time she could get a word in.

812
01:09:56,921 --> 01:10:01,885
Funny thing is, sometimes she'd come home early,

813
01:10:01,968 --> 01:10:04,387
and l'd pretend to be asleep.

814
01:10:04,470 --> 01:10:07,223
Who? You...your mom?

815
01:10:07,307 --> 01:10:08,474
Yeah.

816
01:10:10,602 --> 01:10:13,479
She'd stand in the doorway looking at me.

817
01:10:14,564 --> 01:10:17,108
And l'd just keep my eyes shut.

818
01:10:19,402 --> 01:10:23,448
l knew she just wanted to find out about my day,

819
01:10:23,531 --> 01:10:25,325
that she came home early...

820
01:10:27,660 --> 01:10:30,413
just to talk to me.

821
01:10:32,123 --> 01:10:33,875
And l still wouldn't move.

822
01:10:33,958 --> 01:10:36,503
l'd still pretend to just be asleep.

823
01:10:44,177 --> 01:10:47,764
l don't know why l did that.

824
01:10:59,943 --> 01:11:03,738
We only got a couple hours. Go to sleep.

825
01:11:12,205 --> 01:11:15,667
Captain? Sir?

826
01:11:17,210 --> 01:11:18,670
Corporal?

827
01:11:23,383 --> 01:11:27,053
How you doin' there? You all right?

828
01:11:27,136 --> 01:11:31,474
Yeah, l think this is all good for me, sir.

829
01:11:31,558 --> 01:11:33,935
Really?

830
01:11:34,018 --> 01:11:36,062
How is that?

831
01:11:39,190 --> 01:11:41,860
''War educates the senses,

832
01:11:41,943 --> 01:11:43,945
''calls into action the will,

833
01:11:44,028 --> 01:11:47,115
''perfects the physical constitution,

834
01:11:47,198 --> 01:11:50,160
''brings men into such swift and close collision

835
01:11:50,243 --> 01:11:53,538
''in critical moments that man measures man.''

836
01:11:53,621 --> 01:11:56,332
Yeah, well, l guess that's Emerson's way

837
01:11:56,416 --> 01:11:58,418
of finding the bright side.

838
01:11:58,501 --> 01:12:02,797
- You know Emerson, sir? - l know some.

839
01:12:06,551 --> 01:12:11,097
So where are you from, Captain? What'd you do before the war?

840
01:12:12,682 --> 01:12:14,726
What's the pool up to?

841
01:12:18,438 --> 01:12:22,150
You know, l think it's around 300, sir.

842
01:12:22,233 --> 01:12:24,694
Well, when it gets up to 500,

843
01:12:24,777 --> 01:12:29,073
l'll tell you and we'll split the money, how about that?

844
01:12:29,157 --> 01:12:33,119
Well, sir, l feel it's my duty under your command

845
01:12:33,203 --> 01:12:37,248
to suggest we wait until it gets to a thousand, sir.

846
01:12:39,125 --> 01:12:41,794
What if we don't live that long?

847
01:12:44,172 --> 01:12:47,717
- 500? - 500 would be good, yeah.

848
01:12:47,800 --> 01:12:48,760
Yes, sir.

849
01:12:48,843 --> 01:12:50,220
Yeah.

850
01:12:52,347 --> 01:12:54,098
Get some sleep, Corporal.

851
01:12:54,182 --> 01:12:55,225
Yes, sir.

852
01:14:01,457 --> 01:14:03,251
Who's got sulphur powder?

853
01:14:06,296 --> 01:14:08,673
Medic! My buddy's bleeding!

854
01:14:08,756 --> 01:14:10,091
He needs a tourniquet!

855
01:14:10,175 --> 01:14:12,177
- Wade. - Yes, sir?

856
01:14:12,260 --> 01:14:14,679
- Do what you can. - Yes, sir.

857
01:14:14,762 --> 01:14:16,181
Hold on, fellas.

858
01:14:16,264 --> 01:14:17,765
lt won't be much longer.

859
01:14:17,849 --> 01:14:20,351
How we doing here?

860
01:14:20,435 --> 01:14:21,811
All right.

861
01:14:21,895 --> 01:14:24,272
Yeah, doing all right. Don't worry about it.

862
01:14:24,355 --> 01:14:26,357
Doc's in town.

863
01:14:26,441 --> 01:14:27,775
lt's all right. lt's all right.

864
01:14:27,859 --> 01:14:31,779
The 29th lnfantry's breaking through, they'll be here soon.

865
01:14:31,863 --> 01:14:34,199
Plasma. Anybody got plasma?

866
01:14:34,282 --> 01:14:38,244
- Captain. Hey, Captain. - Soldier, want to fill me in?

867
01:14:38,328 --> 01:14:40,079
Uh, yeah. Lieutenant DeWindt, sir.

868
01:14:40,163 --> 01:14:43,416
99th Troop Carrier Squadron carrying 327th Glider lnfantry.

869
01:14:43,500 --> 01:14:47,253
This one was mine. l was the pilot. 22 dead.

870
01:14:47,337 --> 01:14:51,466
l ended up without a scratch. Took my co-pilot's head off.

871
01:14:51,549 --> 01:14:53,384
Well, who are these people?

872
01:14:53,468 --> 01:14:57,764
The guys we came with, they headed off first night.

873
01:14:57,847 --> 01:15:01,893
Other guys keep showing up. One, two, half-dozen at a time.

874
01:15:01,976 --> 01:15:04,938
Then some officer'll patch together a mixed unit,

875
01:15:05,021 --> 01:15:07,315
head off to make trouble, sir.

876
01:15:07,398 --> 01:15:09,317
We're looking for Private James Ryan.

877
01:15:09,400 --> 01:15:11,611
Baker Company, 506 of the 101st.

878
01:15:11,694 --> 01:15:13,112
No, you got me, sir.

879
01:15:13,196 --> 01:15:14,447
A lot of guys come in and out of here.

880
01:15:15,615 --> 01:15:16,616
Check that squad.

881
01:15:16,699 --> 01:15:20,537
- See if Ryan's in it. - Yes, sir.

882
01:15:21,788 --> 01:15:26,084
Smell that leg right there. ls it south of cheese?

883
01:15:32,465 --> 01:15:33,591
What?

884
01:15:39,138 --> 01:15:41,599
Keep moving. Keep moving!

885
01:15:43,768 --> 01:15:45,603
l'm Juden, you know?

886
01:15:45,687 --> 01:15:48,106
Ju-den.

887
01:15:48,189 --> 01:15:51,192
Yeah, l couldn't pry him out of there,

888
01:15:51,276 --> 01:15:53,486
- l'd need a winch. - Yeah.

889
01:15:57,031 --> 01:15:58,032
Stars.

890
01:15:58,116 --> 01:16:01,244
Yep, Brigadier General Amend,

891
01:16:01,327 --> 01:16:04,122
Deputy Commander, 101st.

892
01:16:04,205 --> 01:16:06,624
Some fucking genius had the idea

893
01:16:06,708 --> 01:16:08,626
of welding steel plates on

894
01:16:08,710 --> 01:16:11,629
to keep the general safe from ground fire.

895
01:16:11,713 --> 01:16:13,923
Unfortunately, they forgot to tell me

896
01:16:14,007 --> 01:16:15,842
until we were getting airborne.

897
01:16:15,925 --> 01:16:17,927
That's like flying a freight train.

898
01:16:18,011 --> 01:16:19,137
OK?

899
01:16:19,220 --> 01:16:20,555
Gross overload.

900
01:16:20,638 --> 01:16:23,349
Trim characteristics all shot to hell.

901
01:16:23,433 --> 01:16:26,436
l nearly broke both my arms keeping her level.

902
01:16:26,519 --> 01:16:28,438
And when...and when we released,

903
01:16:28,521 --> 01:16:32,525
l cut as hard as l could, tried to gain altitude

904
01:16:32,609 --> 01:16:34,569
and still keep from stalling.

905
01:16:34,652 --> 01:16:36,613
Came down like a fucking meteor.

906
01:16:36,696 --> 01:16:39,532
Here's how we ended up.

907
01:16:39,616 --> 01:16:41,659
And the others,

908
01:16:41,743 --> 01:16:44,287
they stopped easy enough OK, though, you know?

909
01:16:44,370 --> 01:16:48,333
We were just...we were just too damn heavy, you know?

910
01:16:48,416 --> 01:16:50,710
The grass was wet.

911
01:16:50,793 --> 01:16:53,129
Downward slope and all.

912
01:16:53,213 --> 01:16:56,049
22 guys dead.

913
01:16:58,259 --> 01:17:00,094
All that for a general?

914
01:17:00,178 --> 01:17:02,305
One man.

915
01:17:04,098 --> 01:17:07,310
- Lot of that going around. - Fubar.

916
01:17:07,393 --> 01:17:08,728
Fubar.

917
01:17:08,811 --> 01:17:10,188
Fubar.

918
01:17:10,271 --> 01:17:11,606
Fubar.

919
01:17:11,689 --> 01:17:13,775
Y'all got that right.

920
01:17:14,984 --> 01:17:18,071
l looked in a German dictionary. There's no ''fubar'' in there.

921
01:17:18,154 --> 01:17:19,239
- Upham. - Yes, sir?

922
01:17:19,322 --> 01:17:21,991
There's more paratroops. Find out if one's Ryan.

923
01:17:22,075 --> 01:17:23,117
Yes, sir.

924
01:17:23,201 --> 01:17:26,204
You might want to check these out, sir.

925
01:17:26,287 --> 01:17:28,081
Dog tags.

926
01:17:28,164 --> 01:17:31,751
More than l really want to count, sir.

927
01:17:31,835 --> 01:17:34,879
l've...l've covered a lot of bodies, sir.

928
01:17:34,963 --> 01:17:37,090
Jackson...

929
01:17:37,173 --> 01:17:38,675
start going through those.

930
01:17:38,758 --> 01:17:39,759
Yes, sir.

931
01:17:41,302 --> 01:17:43,179
l'll help.

932
01:17:44,722 --> 01:17:47,141
What do you think? He in there?

933
01:17:47,225 --> 01:17:49,435
lf he is, l'll find him.

934
01:17:49,519 --> 01:17:51,312
l bet he is.

935
01:17:51,396 --> 01:17:54,440
10 bucks says l nail him first.

936
01:17:54,524 --> 01:17:58,153
- Who we got...? - You don't stand a chance.

937
01:17:58,236 --> 01:18:01,739
- You think he's in here? - Just keep looking.

938
01:18:01,823 --> 01:18:04,033
All right. Gary lanico.

939
01:18:04,117 --> 01:18:05,368
Ben Rubino. Mike Cessacchio.

940
01:18:05,451 --> 01:18:07,704
All the Guineas are buying it, huh?

941
01:18:07,787 --> 01:18:10,123
Oh, come on, not the right name.

942
01:18:10,206 --> 01:18:12,375
Wee Willie Winkie, that's your buddy.

943
01:18:12,458 --> 01:18:14,669
We gotta find this prick.

944
01:18:18,923 --> 01:18:21,176
Where is this sonofabitch?

945
01:18:21,259 --> 01:18:24,387
Don't mix them up? Keep them in your pile.

946
01:18:24,470 --> 01:18:26,389
How will l know who's here?

947
01:18:26,472 --> 01:18:29,267
Why don't you just shut up, Reiben, all right?

948
01:18:29,350 --> 01:18:30,685
Everybody be friends.

949
01:18:30,768 --> 01:18:32,353
Cranky there, huh?

950
01:18:33,771 --> 01:18:35,148
l got a winner.

951
01:18:35,231 --> 01:18:36,608
What you talking about?

952
01:18:36,691 --> 01:18:38,067
Ryan.

953
01:18:38,151 --> 01:18:39,194
Ryan?

954
01:18:39,277 --> 01:18:41,112
Look at that, Mellish.

955
01:18:41,196 --> 01:18:44,866
You're a genius, you really are. R-l-E-N-N-E.

956
01:18:44,949 --> 01:18:48,328
That's Rienne. That's French. You know what that means?

957
01:18:48,411 --> 01:18:49,704
lt means nothing.

958
01:18:49,787 --> 01:18:54,083
- Three of a kind. - All from New York.

959
01:18:54,167 --> 01:18:55,668
Do you need a hand with that?

960
01:18:55,752 --> 01:18:57,170
l got a full house.

961
01:18:57,253 --> 01:18:59,172
Got you beat. Straight flush.

962
01:18:59,255 --> 01:19:02,675
You were looking at my tags. You're cheating, you know?

963
01:19:02,759 --> 01:19:03,843
Ryan.

964
01:19:03,927 --> 01:19:05,553
Fuckin' unreal, this guy.

965
01:19:05,637 --> 01:19:07,055
Do you need a hand with that?

966
01:19:07,138 --> 01:19:08,431
Can you read that shit?

967
01:19:08,515 --> 01:19:10,850
Jesus, look at this poor bastard.

968
01:19:10,934 --> 01:19:12,602
They're not bulletproof, huh?

969
01:19:12,685 --> 01:19:14,103
Guess not. All right?

970
01:19:14,187 --> 01:19:15,605
What's between his ears?

971
01:19:15,688 --> 01:19:19,108
Sort of what you fellas got between your legs.

972
01:19:19,192 --> 01:19:21,653
We got to give him that.

973
01:19:21,736 --> 01:19:23,571
Not bad, Jackson.

974
01:19:23,655 --> 01:19:28,117
What the hell are you doing? The whole Airborne's watching.

975
01:19:28,201 --> 01:19:29,327
These aren't chips.

976
01:19:29,410 --> 01:19:32,997
- All right, all right. - Put 'em back in!

977
01:19:56,938 --> 01:19:58,606
He's not here.

978
01:20:01,359 --> 01:20:02,694
Put 'em back.

979
01:20:02,777 --> 01:20:05,613
Maybe we should split into groups, huh?

980
01:20:05,697 --> 01:20:08,324
Wander the woods, calling his name.

981
01:20:08,408 --> 01:20:10,994
He'll hear us sooner or later. Ryan!

982
01:20:11,077 --> 01:20:14,789
That might be a little hard to do, Captain.

983
01:20:14,873 --> 01:20:18,084
Maybe the locals... Hey, you know... uh, excusez-moi.

984
01:20:18,168 --> 01:20:20,128
Parlez-vous Ryan, James Ryan?

985
01:20:20,211 --> 01:20:21,796
Merci. Merci beaucoup.

986
01:20:21,880 --> 01:20:23,840
Ryan! Anybody know Ryan, 101st Airborne?

987
01:20:23,923 --> 01:20:26,050
Ryan? You know a guy named Ryan?

988
01:20:26,134 --> 01:20:27,969
Private James Ryan from lowa?

989
01:20:28,052 --> 01:20:30,805
Anybody know a Ryan?

990
01:20:30,889 --> 01:20:31,931
James Ryan?!

991
01:20:32,015 --> 01:20:35,768
Hey, Joe, doesn't, uh, Michaelson

992
01:20:35,852 --> 01:20:38,897
pal around with a Ryan from ''C'' Company?

993
01:20:38,980 --> 01:20:40,064
l think so.

994
01:20:40,148 --> 01:20:42,275
Bring him up here, would you?

995
01:20:51,284 --> 01:20:52,619
You know Private Ryan?

996
01:20:52,702 --> 01:20:54,162
You're gonna have to speak up, sir.

997
01:20:54,245 --> 01:20:56,831
Speak up, sir! My hearing's not good!

998
01:20:56,915 --> 01:20:58,166
lt comes and goes!

999
01:20:58,249 --> 01:21:00,376
A grenade went off by me!

1000
01:21:00,460 --> 01:21:04,088
Got it, got it. Do you know Private Ryan?

1001
01:21:04,172 --> 01:21:05,215
Who?

1002
01:21:05,298 --> 01:21:08,968
- Private Ryan? James Ryan? - Jimmy Ryan?

1003
01:21:09,052 --> 01:21:12,055
James. James Francis Ryan.

1004
01:21:12,138 --> 01:21:14,933
No, no, no. James Francis Ryan.

1005
01:21:15,016 --> 01:21:18,019
Get me a pencil, something to write on.

1006
01:21:18,102 --> 01:21:19,979
Quick! Come on, a pencil!

1007
01:21:22,315 --> 01:21:24,108
A small one, sir.

1008
01:21:24,818 --> 01:21:26,236
Write this down.

1009
01:21:26,319 --> 01:21:28,071
James Francis Ryan, question mark.

1010
01:21:28,154 --> 01:21:30,448
lowa, question mark.

1011
01:21:30,532 --> 01:21:32,659
Do you know know him?

1012
01:21:32,742 --> 01:21:33,952
Read the message. Look.

1013
01:21:36,621 --> 01:21:38,748
Yeah. Of course l know him, sir.

1014
01:21:38,832 --> 01:21:40,375
Where is he?

1015
01:21:43,920 --> 01:21:44,921
Yeah, yeah.

1016
01:21:45,004 --> 01:21:48,049
We missed our drop zone by 20 miles,

1017
01:21:48,132 --> 01:21:51,052
ended up by Bumville or some damn place.

1018
01:21:51,135 --> 01:21:54,305
We were coming here to the rally point,

1019
01:21:54,389 --> 01:21:57,642
ran into a colonel who was gathering up men

1020
01:21:57,725 --> 01:22:01,020
- to go to, uh...Ramelle... - Ramelle.

1021
01:22:01,104 --> 01:22:03,898
Babysitting a bridge. That's all l know, sir.

1022
01:22:03,982 --> 01:22:05,650
Great! Great! Thank...thank you.

1023
01:22:05,733 --> 01:22:07,819
Write ''thank you.'' Read, and thank you.

1024
01:22:07,902 --> 01:22:09,154
You're welcome!

1025
01:22:09,237 --> 01:22:10,405
Assemble on me.

1026
01:22:12,615 --> 01:22:14,200
Thank you, Lieutenant.

1027
01:22:17,287 --> 01:22:19,539
Ramelle.

1028
01:22:19,622 --> 01:22:22,917
We're here. There.

1029
01:22:23,001 --> 01:22:24,085
Ramelle...

1030
01:22:24,169 --> 01:22:28,131
is on the Merderet river, just south-west of us.

1031
01:22:28,214 --> 01:22:31,926
You know anything about this bridge, Captain?

1032
01:22:32,010 --> 01:22:35,388
Yep. The target has always been Cherbourg.

1033
01:22:35,471 --> 01:22:39,184
We can't push on Paris without a deep water port,

1034
01:22:39,267 --> 01:22:40,852
Rommel knows that,

1035
01:22:40,935 --> 01:22:45,398
so he's gonna try to get his armour across the river.

1036
01:22:45,481 --> 01:22:50,445
Then he can hit us in the flank when we turn to Cherbourg.

1037
01:22:50,528 --> 01:22:55,658
That makes any village with a bridge solid-gold real estate.

1038
01:23:15,970 --> 01:23:17,972
Let's go.

1039
01:23:26,773 --> 01:23:28,566
Captain.

1040
01:24:06,813 --> 01:24:08,481
What the hell is that?

1041
01:24:10,233 --> 01:24:13,444
A radar site. Must be out of action.

1042
01:24:13,528 --> 01:24:15,655
Looks like there's something in that...

1043
01:24:15,738 --> 01:24:18,199
sandbag bunker right under the station.

1044
01:24:19,242 --> 01:24:20,243
See it?

1045
01:24:20,326 --> 01:24:22,203
Yeah. That's my guess, too.

1046
01:24:23,872 --> 01:24:26,249
What is it?

1047
01:24:26,332 --> 01:24:28,626
Machine gun. Probably MG-42.

1048
01:24:28,710 --> 01:24:31,004
Jesus. ls that what got those guys?

1049
01:24:31,087 --> 01:24:33,590
Maybe one of them's our boy.

1050
01:24:33,673 --> 01:24:36,092
No, their patches are 82nd.

1051
01:24:36,176 --> 01:24:39,053
l don't know how fast you guys are,

1052
01:24:39,137 --> 01:24:42,932
but let's detour this way, they'll never know we were here.

1053
01:24:44,058 --> 01:24:48,062
So, Captain, let's just go around it.

1054
01:24:48,146 --> 01:24:51,858
l hear what you're saying, but we can't.

1055
01:24:51,941 --> 01:24:55,069
l'm with Reiben on this one, sir.

1056
01:24:55,153 --> 01:24:58,865
- We left them 88s. - For the Air Force.

1057
01:24:58,948 --> 01:25:02,952
The Air Force won't spend ordinance on one machine gun.

1058
01:25:03,036 --> 01:25:05,163
Uh, Captain...

1059
01:25:05,246 --> 01:25:08,249
We skip it and still accomplish our mission.

1060
01:25:08,333 --> 01:25:10,919
l mean, this isn't our mission, right?

1061
01:25:11,002 --> 01:25:14,547
That's what you want to do, just leave it here?

1062
01:25:14,631 --> 01:25:16,674
Let them ambush the next company?

1063
01:25:16,758 --> 01:25:21,221
No, sir, l'm simply saying, it seems like an unnecessary risk

1064
01:25:21,304 --> 01:25:22,555
given our objective, sir.

1065
01:25:22,639 --> 01:25:24,933
Our objective is to win the war.

1066
01:25:27,894 --> 01:25:32,398
Sir, l just, uh, l don't have a good feeling about this one.

1067
01:25:33,983 --> 01:25:37,570
When was the last time you felt good about anything?

1068
01:25:59,217 --> 01:26:02,262
